         <div>
            <head>24.6.1883 Sonntag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName> 24. June 1883. Sunday</p>
            <p>Went to <placeName key="59496">Wandsbeck</placeName> to <persName key="1184">Nita&#x2019;s</persName>. In the train from <placeName key="59496">Wandsbeck</placeName>
               to Groß Juthorn there was an old Jew who had paid 25 Pfennigs for the one tram and
               was now told to pay 6 more. He kicked up as much row as if he was going to be hung.
                  <hi rend="dc">&#x201e;Es ist eine Schinderei, eine Schinderei, ich werde es der Direktion
                  melden, Ich kenne die Direktion, es is ja eine Schinderei.&#x201c;</hi> he howled at the
               top of his voice through the whole carriage. <persName key="1181">Willy
                  Kempff</persName>, and the <persName key="1239">Hartmeyer&#x2019;s</persName> were at
                  <persName key="1184">Nita&#x2019;s</persName>. In the evening we saw a very curious scene
               in the forest: a drunken lover and his bride. He had got her around the waist and
               reeled about with her in a most comical way. This morning I went to the <placeName key="56623">English Church</placeName>, into <persName key="10989">Pearson</persName>&#x2019;s pew. I had not been in long before another man stalked in; I
               was of course very uncomfortable, as I know nobody but <persName key="1240">Dickens</persName>, thinking it was his brother. But it turned out to be a German
               who was just as frightened of me as I was of him.</p>
            <p>
               <note type="com">Die Rede des Juden ist in deutscher Schrift geschrieben.</note>
            </p>
